The problem of agency in the acquisition os ownership and possession, upon which there is a good deal· in this Title, may be stated thus 2-Wi11 delivery of possession, or conveyance of ownership, to B, acting as agent for A, make A possessor or owner without more, or is it necessary that there shall be a second conveyance from B to A? This question the old law answered in the negative: it tolerated only one necessary exception. Some persons, viz. slaves, filiifamilias, and those in manu or mancipio, could not hold property owing to their subjection to a superior: if ownership or possession (as to the latter there was a doubt in respect of those in manu or mancipio, Gaius ii. 90) was transferred to them, the conveyance, unless it was to be nugatory, must enure solely to the benefit of the superior : they served solely as conduit-pipes through whom rights passed instantaneously to the latter, Gaius ii. 86-88. Other gradun] modifications of the strict old rule are noticed in the text and following notes.
